eMeanings":[{"name":"Bradshaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Bradshaw in Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Derbyshire, from Old English <i>brād</i> ‘broad’ + <i>sceaga</i> ‘thicket’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brayshaw","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Bradshaw  , reflecting the local Yorkshire pronunciation."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh Bradshaw was born in 1355, in Westleigh, Lancashire, England, his father, Roger Leigh Bradshaw, was 60 and his mother, Miss Osbaldeston-Bradhaigh, was 40. He married Margaret de Verdun 2nd Baroness de Verdun in 1377, in Blackrod, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 28 August 1383, in Calais, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1355–28 August 1383":"1355–28. august 1383","1345–1417":"1345–1417","1355–1383":"1355–1383","1351–1436":"1351–1436","1378–1415":"1378–1415","1295–1382":"1295–1382","1315–1361":"1315–1361","27 AUG 1382":"27. august 1382","1351":"1351","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1415":"1415","1315":"1315","1436":"1436","1336":"1336","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","28 August 1383":"28. august 1383","1417":"1417","Blackrod, Lancashire, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blackrod Lancashire England":"Blackrod, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Haigh, Lancashire, England":"Haigh, Lancashire, England","Blackrod, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Blackrod, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Old Hall, Westleigh, Lancashire, England":"Westleigh, Lancashire, England","Calais, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Calais, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1355–28 August 1383":"1355–28. elokuuta 1383","1345–1417":"1345–1417","1355–1383":"1355–1383","1351–1436":"1351–1436","1378–1415":"1378–1415","1295–1382":"1295–1382","1315–1361":"1315–1361","27 AUG 1382":"27. elokuuta 1382","1351":"1351","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1415":"1415","1315":"1315","1436":"1436","1336":"1336","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","28 August 1383":"28. elokuuta 1383","1417":"1417","Blackrod,